	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Kenyan producers hope to target growing EU avocado market </h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Kenya Horticulture Competiveness Project has released a report highlighting the scope for increased avocado exports to the EU, if current Kenyan production can be expanded. Avocado farming in Kenya is mostly practised ‘in Central Kenya and the Rift Valley, mostly in tea and coffee growing regions where the crop does well’.</p><p>Much of the growing demand in the EU (up 23% since 2006) is attributed to ‘increased awareness of the fruit and its potential uses and benefits’, and producing countries such as South Africa, Chile, Israel and Peru have been among those recently been running consumer awareness campaigns in Europe. France is currently the largest EU consumer of avocados, and, along with Spain and Netherlands, is an important redistribution centre for the trade.</p><p>Of the main African producers, ‘Kenya, South Africa, Rwanda, Democratic Republic of Congo and Cameroon together accounted for 12 percent of world output in 2008’, but at present Kenya’s share of the EU avocado market is in decline (down from 8% in 2006 to 7% in 2010). Kenyan avocado producers have expressed concerns about the recurrent cost implications of food safety and private compliance requirements, such as the British Retail Consortium standards, which are used by some supermarket retailers and are more onerous than the widely accepted GLOBALGAP standards.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Coastweek.com</i>, ‘Farmers look to bonanza from avocado exports’, 11 July 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=83260" target="_self">http://www.freshplaza.com/news_detail.asp?id=83260</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Current opportunities in the EU avocado market highlight the need for ACP horticultural producers to remain responsive to evolving patterns of consumer demand, and the market research carried out also highlights the growing international competition in serving the EU market. However while preferential access is being granted to a growing number of third-country suppliers, the report from Kenya suggests that it is production capacity constraints that represent the most significant constraint on expanded Kenyan avocado exports to the EU. </p><p>The report also highlights the central importance of attaining the required quality standards, while at the same time minimising the administrative costs of compliance verification. This potentially constitutes an area where donor support and EU policy initiatives could assist, for example through:</p><p>a)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; support for better organisation among smallholder farmers (e.g. via producer associations), in order to increase the size of each production unit requiring compliance certification, thereby reducing the unit cost;</p><p>b)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; support to the development of regionally based certification agencies;</p><p>c)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; greater harmonisation of regulatory and compliance approval procedures across various public and private sector schemes, in order to reduce the numbers of compliance verification exercises required when serving the EU market.</p><p>The Kenyan horticulture sector has achieved some success in dialogue around these issues, in terms of the transposition of GLOBALGAP standards into standards more relevant to local production realities via the KENYAGAP set of standards.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
